1 Data Loading & Description

In this script, only HIV- patients (Live Cells) are analyzed.

Three patients are available TFH041, TFH095 and TFH146. It is important to note that there has been a naming switch between Tfh and Live Cells for patient TFH041.

Before filtering according Samâ€™s thresholds (keep cells with more/equal than 750 UMIs and 400 genes), we observe that TF041 has a low number of good quality cells from PBMC sample - see figure below and script_070517_ExploratoryStudy_TFH041.html. The number of UMIs and detected genes seem quite close between patients (except TFH041), we might observe a technical effect after aggregation of those patients together.

###--- Filtering
##- TFH041
#- LN
TFH041_LN <- TFH041_LN[, which(apply(TFH041_LN, 2, function(x) sum(x != 0)) >= 400 & apply(TFH041_LN, 2, sum) >= 750)]
TFH041_LN <- TFH041_LN[which(apply(TFH041_LN, 1, sum) != 0), ] # 15,731 genes & 727 cells
#- PBMC
TFH041_PBMC <- TFH041_PBMC[, which(apply(TFH041_PBMC, 2, function(x) sum(x != 0)) >= 400 & apply(TFH041_PBMC, 2, sum) >= 750)]
TFH041_PBMC <- TFH041_PBMC[which(apply(TFH041_PBMC, 1, sum) != 0), ] # 3,345 genes & 12 cells
#- Merging
TFH041 <- rbind.fill(as.data.frame(t(TFH041_LN)), as.data.frame(t(TFH041_PBMC)))
rownames(TFH041) <- c(paste(colnames(TFH041_LN), 'LN', sep = '_'), paste(colnames(TFH041_PBMC), 'PBMC', sep = '_'))
dim(TFH041) # 739 cells & 15,731 genes
TFH041[is.na(TFH041)] <- 0
TFH041 <- as.data.frame(t(TFH041))

##- TFH095
#- LN
TFH095_LN <- TFH095_LN[, which(apply(TFH095_LN, 2, function(x) sum(x != 0)) >= 400 & apply(TFH095_LN, 2, sum) >= 750)]
TFH095_LN <- TFH095_LN[which(apply(TFH095_LN, 1, sum) != 0), ] # 15,466 genes & 558 cells
#- PBMC
TFH095_PBMC <- TFH095_PBMC[, which(apply(TFH095_PBMC, 2, function(x) sum(x != 0)) >= 400 & apply(TFH095_PBMC, 2, sum) >= 750)]
TFH095_PBMC <- TFH095_PBMC[which(apply(TFH095_PBMC, 1, sum) != 0), ] # 14,740 genes & 564 cells
#- Merging
TFH095 <- rbind.fill(as.data.frame(t(TFH095_LN)), as.data.frame(t(TFH095_PBMC)))
rownames(TFH095) <- c(paste(colnames(TFH095_LN), 'LN', sep = '_'), paste(colnames(TFH095_PBMC), 'PBMC', sep = '_'))
dim(TFH095) # 1,122 cells & 17,575 genes
TFH095[is.na(TFH095)] <- 0
TFH095 <- as.data.frame(t(TFH095))

##- TFH146
#- LN

TFH146_LN <- TFH146_LN[which(apply(TFH146_LN, 1, sum) != 0), ] # 14,946 genes & 417 cells
#- PBMC
TFH146_PBMC <- TFH146_PBMC[, which(apply(TFH146_PBMC, 2, function(x) sum(x != 0)) >= 400 & apply(TFH146_PBMC, 2, sum) >= 750)]
TFH146_PBMC <- TFH146_PBMC[which(apply(TFH146_PBMC, 1, sum) != 0), ] # 12,391 genes & 409 cells

TFH146[is.na(TFH146)] <- 0

After filtering according Samâ€™s thresholds (keep cells with more/equal than 750 UMIs and 400 genes - R code above), we have

  • TFH041 - 739 cells & 15,731 genes
    • 727 cells & 15,731 genes - LN sample
    • 12 cells & 3,345 genes - PBMC sample
  • TFH095 - 1,122 cells & 17,575 genes
    • 558 cells & 15,466 genes - LN sample
    • 564 cells & 14,740 genes - PBMC sample
  • TFH146 - 826 cells & 16,230 genes
    • 417 cells & 14,946 genes - LN sample
    • 409 cells & 12,391 genes - PBMC sample

2 Seurat Analysis

As in Gierahn et al. (2017), library-size normalization is performed for each cell. UMI-collapsed gene expression values for each cell barcode were scaled by the total number of transcripts and multiplied by 10,000. Scaled expression data were then natural-log transformed before analysis using Seurat.

###--- Merging
data_HIVneg <- rbind.fill(as.data.frame(t(TFH041)), as.data.frame(t(TFH095)), as.data.frame(t(TFH146)))
rownames(data_HIVneg) <- c(paste(colnames(TFH041), 'TFH041', sep = '_'), paste(colnames(TFH095), 'TFH095', sep = '_'), paste(colnames(TFH146), 'TFH146', sep = '_'))
dim(data_HIVneg) # 2,687 cells & 21,224 genes
data_HIVneg[is.na(data_HIVneg)] <- 0
data_HIVneg <- as.data.frame(t(data_HIVneg))

###--- Normalization
#- Seurat object - log2-transformation & library-size normalization - done on Rhino - why? issue with R 3.4.0
seuratObj <- new('seurat', raw.data = data_HIVneg)
seuratObj <- Setup(seuratObj, min.cells = 0, min.genes = 0, project = 'Pantaleo', total.expr = 10000) # filtering already done - see above
#- Output
saveRDS(seuratObj, file = 'Output_071817/HIVnegativePatients.rds')
seuratObj <- readRDS('Output_071817/HIVnegativePatients.rds') # 2,687 cells & 21,224 genes

The single cell dataset likely contains uninteresting sources of variation. This could include not only technical noise, but batch effects, or even biological sources of variation (cell cycle stage). As suggested in Buettner et al. (2015), regressing these signals out of the analysis can improve downstream dimensionality reduction and clustering. Seurat implements a basic version of this by constructing linear models to predict gene expression based on user-defined variables. Seurat stores the z-scored residuals of these models in the scale.data slot, and they are used for dimensionality reduction and clustering. We typically regress out cell-cell variation in gene expression driven by batch (if applicable), cell alignment rate (as provided by Drop-seq tools for Drop-seq data), the number of detected molecules and mitochondrial gene expression. For cycling cells, we can also learn a cell-cycle score (as in Macosko et al. (2015)) and Regress this out as well - from Gierahn et al. (2017).
Here, we simply regress on the number of UMIs per cell as well as the percentage mitochondrial gene content.

###--- Regress out unwanted sources of variation
mito.genes <- grep("^MT-", rownames(seuratObj@data), value = TRUE)
percent.mito <- colSums(as.matrix(expm1(seuratObj@data[mito.genes, ]))) / colSums(as.matrix(expm1(seuratObj@data)))

batch <- sapply(str_split(colnames(seuratObj@data), '_'), function(x) paste(x[2], x[3], sep = '_'))
batch <- as.factor(batch)
seuratObj <- AddMetaData(seuratObj, percent.mito, 'percent.mito')

seuratObj <- AddMetaData(seuratObj, batch, 'batch')
GenePlot(seuratObj, 'nUMI', 'percent.mito')
GenePlot(seuratObj, 'nUMI', 'nGene') # 0.94
#- remove unwanted sources of variation
seuratObj <- RegressOut(seuratObj, latent.vars = c('nUMI', 'percent.mito', 'batch')) # remove effect of CDR (high correlation between nGene and nUMI - 0.94) and mitochondrial effect

Seurat calculates highly variable genes and focuses on these for downstream analysis.

###--- Detection of variable genes across the single cells
seuratObj <- MeanVarPlot(seuratObj, fxn.x = expMean, fxn.y = logVarDivMean, x.low.cutoff = 0.25, x.high.cutoff = 3, y.cutoff = 0.5, do.contour = FALSE)
length(seuratObj@var.genes) # 743 highly variable genes

We identify 743 highly variable genes with log-mean expression values greater than 0.25 and dispersion (variance/mean) greater than 0.5.

###--- PCA
#- PCA performed on the scaled data and using only highly variable genes
seuratObj <- PCA(seuratObj, pc.genes = seuratObj@var.genes)
seuratObj <- ProjectPCA(seuratObj)

We can identify markers that are strongly correlated with cellular heterogeneity - see below. We can observe some known cell markers (ILR7, NKG7 and GZMA).

One thousand iterations of the t-SNE algorithm (Barnes-hut implementation) using a perplexity value of 40 and the first top 8 principal components is performed. Those first top 8 PCs were chosen according to the standard deviation - see below.

###--- tSNE
seuratObj <- RunTSNE(seuratObj, dims.use = 1:8, perplexity = 40, do.fast = TRUE)

Letâ€™s look at the tSNE plots now - perplexity of 40 and 1,000 iterations of the Barnes-Hut implementation.

A batch/patient effect is easily observed here. Patient TFH146 - LN seems to be different than the two others. This patient has been analyzed/sequenced in June, while TFH041 and TFH095 have been analyzed/sequenced in July.

Letâ€™s look at some cell markers.

We confirm that TFH146 - PBMC has a really low number of B cells. Of course, we observe T cells (CD4 and CD8), NK cells and Monocytes.

It doesnâ€™t look so bad - from PBMC we are able to see expression of T cells, NK cells, Monocytes and sometimes B cells; from LN we are able to observe T cells, B cells, NK cells and Monocytes.
